title: For Trade:  92 dodge dynasty FT AR
postcontent: 1992 Dodge Dynasty. The vehicle has a smooth running 3.0L V6 engine and automatic transmission. The transmission shifts fantastic and has no known issues.  link for pics http://dayton.craigslist.org/cto/REDACTED.html I drive it daily, Dayton to Miamisburg, roughly 15 highway miles each way - no problems!  The body is pretty clean with minimal rust. The tire treads are in good condition. The interior is just about perfect with the exception of the dash pad is slightly warped from the sun. I've recently replaced the headliner. Power locks and windows, all work great. Passenger front door opens only from inside (linkage?). The radio shows time but does nothing else. Also, the blower motor is inop. Have not diagnosed but may just be resistor or motor. Control unit appears to command actuators and modes as designed.   The odometer stopped working on the previous owner, however according to his title he had only put a few hundred miles on it before it broke and I've put maybe 200 miles on it since. The odometer currently around 120K miles. Also, at highway speeds there is a slight vibration/shimmy felt in the steering wheel, not sure if tires need balanced. Other than that, it's a dependable car and fires up and drives each morning  Mechanically, it is a rather sound car - after I bought it I replaced a brake line going to the driver's rear drum. The only engine faults I know of is the ECT (engine coolant temp) sensor is bad - the gauge on the dash is pegged to Cold and does not move - being a NTC type sensor, I assume the sensor is the culprit (excessive resistance in sensor).   The car has a new fuel pump and fuel tank installed by the previous owner.   I daily drive this vehicle while I work on my other cars - i just finished a major repair on my Jeep and it's now road worthy so i am looking to sell the Dynasty.   I put down everything I know that is possibly wrong with it, and will not hide any issues - I don't need to sell the car but a few of my project jeeps are done so it can go if need be - I've gone over the car pretty well as a former ASE certified flat rate tech with a local Jeep/Chrysler/Dodge dealership- and this car is in impressive condition! Please don't hesitate to ask questions or make an offer! As a good Christian man, I've disclosed everything I currently know about the car's condition! title: For Sale:  Richmond Armory Civil War rifled Musket .58 CSA richmond .58 Caliber Ball
postcontent: This is a very rare rifled musket 58 caliber .high hump type lock .made for the confederacy in 1861 the first few months of production .just turned 150 years old ....lock marked Richmond VA and dated 1861 ..they only made about 2000 of these and most confederate guns were used to fight the war of northern aggression [ my southern friends like that phrase. The gun has a shoot able bore with a little bit of pitting ...the stock is good and solid with only a couple dings. The barrel bands are marked with the letter *U*. The butt plate has a us on it ..the front cap appears to be made of pewter ..the hammer is a hand made version typically seen on southern guns that were used alot during the course of the war,and as flayerman's says there are no common confederate guns. No FFL needed for these rifle.
